1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
 [MUSIC]

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:40,000
 That Bell Labs bunch of smart people, I call it 1200 PhD level people in Murray Hill in basically one giant building.

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 And so that's a lot of people rubbing up against each other, and they're all doing technical kinds of things.

4
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
 And the environment did not tell people what to do. It was go do your thing.

5
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 And once a year, one side of one piece of paper, tell us what you did, and that will determine how much money you get next year, but it was a very long cycle.

6
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 The one extra thing is that it was a problem-rich environment.

7
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 And so there were things that you could work on, and there was this, I think, very gentle gravitational drift towards doing something that somebody else might care about.

8
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 Lots of people, you know, who cares what other people think, I'm going to do my stuff.

9
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:26,000
 But I think most people got some reward, you know, psychic reward from, I do something, I give it to you, and you say, that was great.

10
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 And then you say, but, and you tell me all the things that aren't yet great.

11
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:43,000
 But that kind of thing was very common at the labs, because AT&T at that time basically supplied telephone service to most of the United States, a million people, all kinds of interesting problems in and around communications.

12
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:50,000
 And so no matter what you were interested in, there would be some part of AT&T that could probably make use of that.

13
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:58,000
 So that was part of it, but then there was the external world as well, the research community Bell Labs was just part of the academic research community.

14
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 So they're both outlets, and the labs was perfectly happy to have people do either.

15
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:06,000
 And so all of that, I think, worked out really very well.

16
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:17,000
 And it helped to have stable funding, because basically at that point, if you made a long-distance phone call in the United States, remember the concept of long-distance, right, if you made one of those calls,

17
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 a tiny slice of the revenue of that financed Bell Labs with the charter of make the service better.

18
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 And we won't worry about the details of how you do that.

19
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 So at the time, there was a lot of interest in programming languages.

20
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 This all came out of the Multics experience, right, where people at Bell Labs and, of course, the folks at MIT had realized that writing things in a high-level language made sense.

21
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 And then the question is, what's the high-level language?

22
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 And they started with PL1, which in the abstract sounded like a good idea, and in reality was a horrible idea, because it was a horrible language.

23
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 And so Martin Richards from Cambridge, University of Cambridge, had this language called BCPL.

24
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:08,000
 And he had spent, if I understand it correctly, a sabbatical year at MIT, planted the language in some sense.

25
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 And it was much simpler, much cleaner, much better suited to system programming kinds of things than any version of PL1 would have been.

26
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 And so the people at Bell Labs, Ken Thompson, Dennis Ritchie, and so on, had gotten some experience with high-level languages as suitable for writing lots of different things.

27
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 BCPL wasn't a suitable thing for modern machines because it was typeless.

28
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 And newer machines clearly were coming on stream that would have types like bytes and integers and maybe bigger things.

29
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:55,000
 And so at some point Ken did a lot of experimenting, Ken Thompson did a lot of experimenting with simpler versions, even of BCPL, a particular one called B, which was an interpretive language, no compiler.

30
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 And that was, again, expressive enough that people started to like it. And that's sort of where I started in on this.

31
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 I mean, I had written bits of PL1. It was awful. I'd written Fortran better.

32
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 But the B was sort of nicer to use, but it was still typeless and an interpreter as well, so it wouldn't be terribly efficient.

33
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 But with the PDP-11 in the offing, and I don't remember the exact timing here, it was clear that a version of something that felt sort of like B,

34
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 but which had some mechanism to include types so that you could talk about characters or integers, was going to be the way to go.

35
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 And that's where Dennis picked up and started developing the C language and the compiler to go with it and so on.

36
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 The portability was very much on people's minds at that time, because although the core UNIX work was done on the PDP-11,

37
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 there were other machines at the time that were in the same equivalence class.

38
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 Interdata had a couple of 732, 832 numbers like that. And I think there were probably HP machines as well, etc.

39
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 And the other thing that was in some ways harder was that there was the big mainframe kind of computers that were used by the local computer center.

40
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 And these were fundamentally stripped down versions of the Multics machines. They were GE 635 kind of things.

41
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 And so those were big, clunky, word-oriented machines. They were, in effect, IBM 7094s, cleaned up a bit.

42
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 And getting something that would compile sensibly for those machines that really didn't have characters in a language

43
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 which had become what it was so it could manipulate characters, I think there was a bit of a strain there.

44
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 But that portability, how do you get the same language to work on different computers?

45
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 And Dennis's original compiler really was targeted at the PDP-11.

46
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 And Steve Johnson came along with a portable C compiler which basically separated the front end.

47
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:08,000
 Let's recognize the language, let's build some intermediate structure, and then let's generate code for different kinds of machines.

48
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 I had written a tutorial on B because I thought it was interesting, maybe I can tell other people how to use it.

49
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 And so when C started to be used, and I became somewhat better at using it, then I basically repurposed the B tutorial,

50
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 brought it forward and made the C tutorial out of it.

51
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 And so I used C for essentially all the software I was writing at that time.

52
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 And I kind of liked it. It was good. It was a nice match for the way people think about computing, I think.

53
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 But also a very nice match for the actual hardware of the time, you could imagine what the compiler was doing.

54
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 All of it was clear, so efficient, expressive, and nicely matched to everything around it.

55
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 And then somewhere in probably 1977, early-ish, I coerced Dennis into writing a book about it.

56
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 First edition came out in '78, and at that point the language was pretty reasonable.

57
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 The book, I think it was right on the cusp of whether structures were fully part of the language or not.

58
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 A bit of overhang there, and I don't remember, but I think probably they were not quite but awful close.

59
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 And since Dennis was doing both compiler and book, it was at least a consistent viewpoint.

60
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:32,000
 Question, can you pick up a structure as a unit and pass it around, or do you have to do something special?

61
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 But that's a milestone. And then the next one is probably the 1988 book and the development of the NCC standard,

62
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 the first standard, which is essentially, again, about the same time.

63
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 And so I think those are the ways I measured. And at that point, call it 1988, give or take, just before you encountered it,

64
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 C was probably just fine for anything you might reasonably want to do.

65
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 And this is probably heresy or something, but I don't think that the changes in evolution since then have bought enough in some sense.

